Created files:
- Packages/com.vtuber-system-base.core-ipc-foundation/Runtime/Core/Connection/ClientSessionManager.cs
    Public sealed class implementing IAsyncDisposable. Drives the
    client-side IPC session lifecycle: initial connect, receive
    loop, drop detection, exponential-backoff reconnect, max-attempt
    PermanentlyDisconnected, and Shutdown-as-clean-Disconnected per
    requirements 2.4 / 5.2 / 5.4 / 5.5 / 5.8.

    Constructor parameters:
        - ITransportAdapter transport     : injected I/O port
        - ClientBindOptions bindOptions   : host/port/connect timeout
        - ConnectionStateMachine sm       : 5-state connection FSM
                                            (task 3.1)
        - ReconnectBackoff backoff        : retry schedule (task 3.2)
        - Func<TimeSpan, CancellationToken, Task>? delay = null
            Optional injection point so unit tests can substitute
            Task.Delay with an instant or never-returning awaitable;
            defaults to System.Threading.Tasks.Task.Delay.
        - Action<ReadOnlyMemory<byte>>? onMessageReceived = null
            Inbound frame sink. Task 7.1 will wire this to
            SystemTextJsonCodec.Decode → MainThreadDispatchQueue.
        - Action<string>? logWarning / logError
            Pluggable log sinks (CoreIpcLogger from task 5.3 will
            adapt Unity's Debug.Log into these callbacks).

    Public surface:
        Task StartAsync(CancellationToken externalToken = default)
            Spawns the worker Task that drives connect / receive /
            reconnect. Throws InvalidOperationException on second
            invocation; throws ObjectDisposedException after Dispose.
        Task ShutdownAsync()
            Sets the shutdown flag, cancels the internal CTS,
            disposes the live IClientConnection if any, awaits the
            worker to drain, then issues a single
            ConnectionState.Disconnected transition with
            isShutdown=true (Req 5.8).
        ValueTask DisposeAsync()
            Calls ShutdownAsync (idempotent) and disposes the CTS.
        IClientConnection? CurrentConnection { get; }
        bool IsShutdownRequested { get; }
        Task RunLoopTask { get; }

    Internal flow (RunAsync on the worker):
        Phase 1 — initial connect:
            1. Disconnected → Connecting.
            2. Loop: ITransportAdapter.ConnectClientAsync.
               - On success: cache IClientConnection, Reset backoff,
                 Connecting → Connected, exit phase 1.
               - On failure: log warning, check ExceededMaxAttempts
                 (give up if true; PermanentlyDisconnected is not
                 reachable from Connecting per task 3.1 — see note
                 below), else NextDelay() + await delay, then
                 Connecting → Disconnected → Connecting and retry.
        Phase 2 — receive + reconnect:
            3. Iterate IClientConnection.ReceiveAsync(ct) and forward
               each frame to onMessageReceived. Handler exceptions
               are swallowed and logged so a single bad envelope
               cannot tear down the loop (Req 5.7 spirit, applied
               client-side).
            4. On clean enumeration end (drop) or thrown exception:
               dispose the connection, clear the cache, transition
               Connected → Reconnecting.
            5. Inner retry loop while in Reconnecting:
               - if backoff.ExceededMaxAttempts:
                   Reconnecting → PermanentlyDisconnected, exit (Req
                   5.5).
               - else NextDelay() + await delay (cancellation-aware).
               - try ConnectClientAsync; on failure stay in
                 Reconnecting and continue (the state machine's hard
                 constraint forbids Connecting → Reconnecting, so
                 failed reconnect attempts keep the FSM in
                 Reconnecting and defer the transient Connecting
                 visit until success).
               - on success: Reconnecting → Connecting → Connected,
                 Reset backoff, return to step 3.
        Cancellation / shutdown:
            - All awaits propagate the worker CancellationToken; the
              never-returning delay used by tests is canceled via
              ct.Register so ShutdownAsync drains promptly.
            - ShutdownAsync issues the final Disconnected transition
              with isShutdown=true regardless of which state the
              worker observed last (Connecting / Connected /
              Reconnecting all have valid edges to Disconnected per
              task 3.1's IsValidTransition).
            - PermanentlyDisconnected is sticky — once reached, no
              Disconnected transition is forced (the FSM rejects it
              and the test in task 3.1 already covers that contract).

    Note on initial-attempt PermanentlyDisconnected:
        The state machine produced by task 3.1 only allows the
        Reconnecting → PermanentlyDisconnected edge, so the
        "永久不在サーバへの初回接続" path cannot reach
        PermanentlyDisconnected without ever achieving Connected.
        Task 3.3's required scenarios all start from a successful
        Connected (タスクの "接続成功→切断→再接続成功" /
        "上限超過での PermanentlyDisconnected") so this is consistent
        with the FSM as built. If task 8.2's
        "クライアント先行起動→サーバ後発起動" scenario needs to reach
        PermanentlyDisconnected from a never-connected state, that
        either (a) needs ReconnectBackoff to retry indefinitely
        without a permanent-failure verdict, or (b) needs the FSM to
        gain a Disconnected → PermanentlyDisconnected edge. The
        current implementation logs an error and gives up silently
        when initial connect attempts are exhausted.

    Threading:
        - The worker runs on Task.Run; its CancellationTokenSource
          is created lazily inside StartAsync and disposed at the
          end of DisposeAsync.
        - _currentConnection / _shutdownRequested / _disposed are
          all guarded by a single instance lock; the FSM has its
          own internal lock so we never hold both at once.

